│ This patch correctly fixes the LLVM bug by requiring the `nuw` (no unsigned wrap) flag for equality comparisons  │
│ between GEP instructions.                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                  │
│ The root cause was that the original code unconditionally allowed folding equality comparisons between GEPs with │
│ the same base pointer, assuming that `gep(ptr, idx1) == gep(ptr, idx2)` if and only if `idx1 == idx2`. However,  │
│ this assumption breaks down when address space wrapping can occur, as demonstrated by the counterexample where   │
│ 8-bit pointers cause different indices (0 and 64) to produce the same wrapped address due to the i32 element     │
│ size (4 bytes) causing the offset 64*4=256 to wrap around to 0 in an 8-bit address space.                        │
│                                                                                                                  │
│ By requiring `NW.hasNoUnsignedWrap()` for equality comparisons, the optimization only applies when we can        │
│ guarantee that the GEP computation won't wrap around the address space, preserving the injectivity of the        │
│ mapping from indices to addresses.                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                  │
│ While this causes some existing tests to fail (because they expect the optimization without `nuw` flags), it     │
│ correctly fixes the unsafe optimization that was causing incorrect code generation in the reproducer case. The   │
│ test failures indicate that those test cases should either include `nuw` flags or not expect the optimization to │
│ occur without proper nowrap guarantees.                                                                          │
